data.name: SMCC_file
data.value: If you do want to compute an effective interaction for coupled-cluster calculations you need to specify three files, one for the interaction itself, one for the kinetic energies of all sp orbits and one for sp data declarations. These files are in turn used as input to coupled-cluster calculations.

data.name: SMCib_choice
data.value: Here you specify if you wish to exclude CIB.

data.name: SMCoulomb_included
data.value: Determine if you wish to include the Coulomb interaction or not.

data.name: SMCsb_choice
data.value: Here you specify if you wish to exclude CSB.

data.name: SMHbar_omega
data.value: The oscillator energy in MeV (We can change a look, if there is some change)

data.name: SMHf_iterations
data.value: Determine whether you want to do Hartree-Fock or not. Options are 1) hf_iterations = 0 or 2) hf_iterations = 1 or any number larger than 0.

data.name: SMHFrenorminteraction_file
data.value: If you do Hartree-Fock, the new interaction is given by this file.

data.name: SMHFspdata_file
data.value: The new single-particle in case you do a Hartree-Fock calculation.

data.name: SMJminmax
data.value: For the NN interaction you need to define the min and max value of J for the partial waves. Typical values are 0 and 6. For the argonne interactions Jmax <= 4. For waves greater than J_max, the Hamiltonian is set to zero in this version of the program.

data.name: SMLab_lmax
data.value: Define the maximum values of l for the model space. For square the model space 2n+l is entirely defined by lab_lmax.

data.name: SMLab_nmax
data.value: Define the maximum values of n for the model space. For square the model space 2n+l is entirely defined by lab_lmax.

data.name: SMMass_nucleus
data.value: Give the number of nucleons, recall that for nocore the results depend on A.

data.name: SMMax_space
data.value: If you do nocore, you need also to specify the cut in 2n+l for the huge space, use 200-300 for interactions like cdbonn or argonne use 300.

data.name: SMOrder_of_interaction
data.value: You can also compute results to a given order in many-body perturbation theory, in this case to third order. For coupled-cluster you have to stay with first order.

data.name: SMOutput_run
data.value: output_run is prefixed to output file for optional printouts, tests etc.

data.name: SMPauli_operator
data.value: Specify the type of model space, three choices: square, triangular or wings. For the nocore calculation you can only use the triangular choice

data.name: SMRenorminteraction_fileI
data.value: Input file for the renormalized NN interaction.

data.name: SMRenorminteraction_fileO
data.value: Output file for the renormalized NN interaction.

data.name: SMSpdata_fileI
data.value: Input file for the set of single-particle orbits, this file can be further manipulated by the effective interaction part.

data.name: SMSpdata_fileO
data.value: Output file for the set of single-particle orbits, this file can be further manipulated by the effective interaction part.

data.name: SMStartenergy_g
data.value: If you do the g-matrix you need to specify the number of starting energies and their corresponding values. Typically you would use some 5 or more starting energies and they should all be smaller than the binding energy of the deuteron in order to avoid poles in the computation of G(w). The present code does not allow you to use positive starting energies. Typical start and end values are listed here. Based on the endpoints of the interval, the next values are generated by the simple algo first_value + interval*i where interval is just end-start/number of values.

data.name: SMStartingEnergy
data.value: You can compute the various diagrams for a given starting energy and then sum folded diagrams to infinite order. Typical starting energies for calculation should correspond to roughly the two-body energy of the valence nucleons. It should be negative since you are dealing with bound systems. If you choose just one starting energy, then no folded diagrams are summed up.

data.name: SMType_of_interaction
data.value: Determine what kind of effective interaction you want and the type of calculation. If you type shell-model, the code will produce an effective interaction taylored to the Oslo shell-model code, separated in three files, one for the pp case, one for pn and one for nn. For coupled-cluster calculations you will produce a file containing the effective interaction, one containing the kinetic energy and one for the total single-particle energies. You can also compute the binding energy of various closed core nuclei. The options are thus 1) open-diagrams for shell-model, 2) coupled-cluster and 3) core-diagrams.

data.name: SMType_of_pot
data.value: Specify the type of NN interaction, here you can use Idaho-A, Idaho-B, CD-bonn, argonnev18, n3lo, argonnev8. There is an important point concerning the different interaction models. Idaho-A and Idaho-B have NO charge-symmetry (CSB) or charge-independence breaking terms (ISB). The Argonne potentials run only with full CSB and CIB. The N3LO and CD-bonn models allow you to run with or without one or both of these terms. NO CSB means that for a given set of qauntum numbers ( a specific partial wave) the neutron-neutron and proton-proton parts are identical. NO CIB means that the proton-proton, neutron-neutron and proton-neutron interactions are equal. Isospin symmetry.

data.name: SMType_of_renormv
data.value: Determine the renormalization procedure you want to do, only one at the time.

data.name: SMVeff_xx
data.value: If you wan to compute an effective interaction for the Oslo shell-model codes, you need to define the names of three files, one for the proton-proton case one for the proton-neutron case and finally one for the neutron-neutron case.

data.name: SMVlowk
data.value: If you do Vlowk you need to specify the number of mesh points for the model space and the large space. You need also to define the cutoff for the model in space in fm^- 1 and the in principal infinite integration limit set it to 20 fm^-1. Recall that the NN interactions is fitted up to 350 MeV.
